DOCUMENT();
loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "Parser.pl",
  "freemanMacros.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl"
);

TEXT(beginproblem());

Context()->variables->add(t=>'Real');
$pi=arctan(1)*4;
$a=random(2,5,1);
$b=random(2,7,1);
$f=Formula("x^3+$a*x+$b");
$yval=$f->substitute(x=>1);
$ans1=1;
$ans2=1/(3+$a);

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
\{textbook_ref_exact("Rogawski ET 2e", "3.8","9") \}

Let \(g(x)\) be the inverse of \(f(x)=$f\). Calculate \(g($yval)\),
without finding a formula for \(g(x)\), and then calculate \(g'($yval)\).
$BR
\(g($yval)\) =  \{ans_rule()\}
$BR
\(g'($yval)\) =  \{ans_rule()\}
END_TEXT
ANS(num_cmp($ans1));
ANS(num_cmp($ans2));

Context()->normalStrings;
Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));

$SOL
Let \(g(x)\) be the inverse of \(f(x) = $f\).  Because
\(f(1) = 1^3 + $a(1) + $b = $yval\), 
it follows that \(g($yval) = 1\).  Moreover, \(f'(x) = 3x^2 + $a\), and
\( g'($yval) = \frac{1}{f'(g($yval))} = \frac{1}{f'(1)} = \frac{1}{3+$a}\). 
END_SOLUTION



